<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-839-948  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 839 948.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 3 1990 v4 n32 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Coast guard sails ahead with CAD; improves development, revisionof damage-control diagrams. (Computer-aided design)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lang, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-aided design (CAD) technology and plotters have aided theCoast Guard's Naval Engineering Division in accelerating thedrafting and revisions of their ship designs and the planning ofthe ships' ability to respond in times of crisis.andP;  Storingdiagrams of the ships in digital format allows technicians toupdate existing file and avoid working from scratch.andP;  CAD toolsalso compress the document production cycle.andP;  The new CAD systemreplaced a costly lithographic method of diagram production.andP;  Thedivision has eight workstations and plans to network the computersin the future.andP;  Also in the plans is goal of moving the technologyfurther up in the design process, such as using three-dimensionalsystems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignShipbuildingProductivityTime ManagementDocument Management SystemsUnited States. Coast Guard.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>